al Church","organization":"Congregational Church of the Upper Houses (later Cromwell CT)","dates":"June 10, 1809 - December 29, 1832","type":"clergy","notes":"Ordained and instituted pastor at the Upper Houses (now Cromwell Middlesex County CT) on June 10, 1809 — his father Rev. Joshua Williams Sr. assisted in his ordination. Spoken of locally as 'priest Williams.' Owned the house built by Rev. Gershom Bulkeley, later known as the 'Joseph Edwards House.' Pastor for 23 years until his death."},{"title":"Founding President of the Friendly Association","organization":"Friendly Association (Upper Houses)","dates":"founded by Williams","type":"civic","notes":"Organized the Friendly Association, was its first president, and active in its support throughout his life."},{"title":"Scribe of the General Association of Connecticut","organization":"General Association of Connecticut","dates":"1825 (at Litchfield)","type":"clergy","notes":"Served as scribe at the 1825 Litchfield meeting of the General Association of Connecticut."}],"education":[{"institution":"Yale College","degree":"Bachelor's degree","year_completed":1805,"field":"Theology","notes":"Graduated Yale 1805 — followed his father's 1780 Yale graduation."}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"death","header":"Father and Yale-student son buried in one grave","body":"Joshua Lewis died December 29, 1832 in the Upper Houses at age 47. The next day his eldest son John Mix Williams — a seventeen-year-old Yale student — also died. Father and son were buried in one grave January 1, 1833 per Joshua Lewis's own written instruction, though they were given separate headstones."}],"slug":"joshua-williams-1785"},"HD0978":{"id":"HD0978","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"X00